There are a few instances where I favor 3N over 4 of a major. And that is when I can count 9 tricks. So, if I have a hand with a doubleton or tripleton honor (A, K, or Q), I might consider 3N when I can count 9 tricks based on the Ogust response. The most obvious example is when I have a doubleton or tripleton honor and 3 Aces. Then, if in response to 2N, partner shows a good suit (2 of the top 3 honors), I can count 9 tricks (six in opener's suit plus 3 aces). Of course, most hands are not that obvious. |
PG| ***** 91 ***** |


AT|

The general rule I use is I "picture" partner having AQxxxx of his suit and nothing else. If I am willing to play 3NT opposite that holding, I would bid Ogust. Similarly, if I am willing to play 3 of our suit with that holding, and 3N if partner has a max, then I also bid Ogust, bidding 3N if partner shows a good hand with a good suit.|
PG| ***** 92 ***** |


AT|

Of course, if I have a maximum opener (18+), I am willing to play game opposite just about any 6 point hand, so I might bid 3N with a balanced hand with 2 card support (or even a singleton if I can count 9 outside tricks). If I have 16 or 17, I would tend to favor 4 of the major over 3N, although if I were willing to play 3 of the major, I might bid Ogust just in case partner shows 8-10 HCP.|
